cat('\n\n')

Here, we generate two plots to evaluate the concordance across three cell-lines; WT and KO phenotype.

  • Peak rank versus Peak enrichment: In this plot, we are looking at each individual sample to evaluate what number of peaks we would retain if thresholding by peak enrichment. It is also valuable to see how this differs between three celllines.
  • Overlapping peaks: The Venn diagram gives us a representation of the number of peaks overlapping between the three celllines. If there is a minimum of 1bp overlap between regions, then it is counted for one overlap. If multiple peaks are overlapping between two samples, connectedPeaks = merge will only add 1 to the overlapping counts.

NFnarrowPeak_tib <- samples 

for (samplename in NFnarrowPeak_tib$samplename) {

  df <- data.frame(peak_enrichment = peaks_file$V7, peak_rank = rank(dplyr::desc(peaks_file$V7))) %>%

2 Binding Profile Assessment

We can use the peak files to calculate the profile of the peaks binding to TSS regions using a package called ChIPseeker. First we prepare the TSS regions, by defining the flanking sequence upstream (10K) and downstream (10K of the TSS sites. Next, ChIPseeker aligns the peaks that mapping to these regions, and uses the enrichment values to generate the tagMatrix. The tagMatrix is used to plot the signal profile for each sample. Confidence intervals are estimated by the bootstrap method and illustrated by the use of shading on the profile plot.

for (sample_ID in NFnarrowPeak_tib$sample) {
  obj <- ChIPpeakAnno::toGRanges(paste0("../data/peakcalls/",sample_ID,"_peaks.narrowPeak"), format="narrowPeak", header=FALSE)  
  assign(paste0(sample_ID,"_grange_file"), obj)
}
library(TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg19.knownGene)
txdb <- TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg19.knownGene #shorthand (for convenience)


library(ChIPseeker)

promoter <- getPromoters(txdb, upstream=5000, downstream=5000)

2.1 Peaks TSS region

Promoter regions of active genes are in an open chromatin state. Ideally, ATAC-seq fragments shorter than 100 bp (i.e., inferred nucleosome-free fragments) should cluster immediately upstream of TSSs.

## this is your tagMatrixList, calculated from your input files (peak1.bed and peak2.bed)
#tagMatrixList <- lapply(files, getTagMatrix, windows=promoter)
peakList <- list(H460_WT = `S7_H460_WT-NF_grange_file`, 
                 H460_KO = `S8_H460_KO-NF_grange_file`,
                 H2009_WT = `S9_H2009_WT-NF_grange_file`,
                 H2009_KO = `S10_H2009_KO-NF_grange_file`, 
                 Calu6_WT = `S11_Calu6_WT-NF_grange_file`,
                 Calu6_KO = `S12_Calu6_KO-NF_grange_file`)


tagMatrixList <- lapply(peakList, getTagMatrix, windows=promoter)

# Plot the binding profiles
plotAvgProf(tagMatrixList, xlim=c(-5000, 5000), facet="row", free_y = TRUE)

    cvglists <- sapply(file.path("../results/NF_bigwigs/", files), import,
